b'' b'(david nye) wrote:' b'' b'' b' there is no means that i can possibly think of to prove beyond doubt' b' that a god does not exist (but if anyone has one, by all means, tell me' b' what it is). therefore, lacking this ability of absolute proof, being an' b' atheist becomes an act of faith in and of itself, and this i cannot accept.' b' i accept nothing on blind faith.' b'' b' invisible pink flying unicorns! need i say more?' b'' b' ...i harbor no beliefs at all, there is no good evidence for god' b' existing or not. some folks call this agnosticism. it does not suffer' b' from "blind faith" at all. i think of it as "don\'t worry, be happy".' b'' b' for many atheists, the lack of belief in gods is secondary to an' b' epistemological consideration: what do we accept as a reliable way of' b' knowing? there are no known valid logical arguments for the existence' b' of gods, nor is there any empirical evidence that they exist. most' b' philosophers and theologians agree that the idea of a god is one that' b' must be accepted on faith. faith is belief without a sound logical' b' basis or empirical evidence. it is a reliable way of knowing?' b'' b'' b'could you expand on your definition of knowing? it seems a bit monolithic' b"here, but i'm not sure that you intend that. don't we need, for example, to" b'distinguish between "knowing" plus equals (or apples plus apples' b'equals apples), the french "knowing" that jerry lewis is an auteur, and' b'what it means to say we "know" what socrates said?' b'' b' this is patently absurd; but whoever wishes to become a philosopher' b' must learn not to be frightened by absurdities. bertrand russell' b'' b'i like this epigraph. perhaps the issue is learning which, if any,' b'absurdities merit further exploration...gene' 